id="archive_intro"><h1>Linux / Unix Security</h1><div
class="format_text"><p>The latest in-depth reviews, guides, news, howtos and other information on  IT security, Linux, open source, firewalls, networks, privacy, encryption, cryptography, attacks, vulnerabilities, and much more ( <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/security/feed/">rss feed</a> ).</p></div></div><div
class="post-354 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-linux-news category-open-source category-security tag-debian-linux tag-kali-linux tag-linux post_box top" id="post-354"><div
class="headline_area"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/linux-news/download-kali-linux-version-1-iso-dvd-images/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent link to Download of the day: Kali Linux ( BackTrack Linux )">Download of the day: Kali Linux ( BackTrack Linux )</a></h2><p
class="headline_meta">by <span
class="author vcard"><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/tips/about-us" rel="author" class="url fn">nixCraft</a></span> on <abbr
class="published" title="2013-03-13">March 13, 2013</abbr> &middot; <span><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/linux-news/download-kali-linux-version-1-iso-dvd-images/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span
class="dsq-postid" rel="354 http://www.cyberciti.biz/?p=354">0 comments</span></a></span></p><p
class="headline_meta">in <span><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/linux-news/" title="View all posts in Linux News" rel="category tag">Linux News</a>, <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/open-source/" title="View all posts in Open Source" rel="category tag">Open Source</a>, <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/security/" title="View all posts in Security" rel="category tag">Security</a></span></p></div><div
class="format_text entry-content"><p><span
class="drop_cap">K</span>ali Linux is  the successor of the BackTrack Penetration Testing Linux distribution has been released. From the official project page:</p><blockquote><p>Kali is a complete re-build of BackTrack Linux, adhering completely to Debian development standards. All-new infrastructure has been put in place, all tools were reviewed and packaged, and we use Git for our VCS.</p></blockquote><p
class="to_comments"><span
class="bracket">{</span> <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/linux-news/download-kali-linux-version-1-iso-dvd-images/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span>0</span> comments</a> <span
class="bracket">}</span></p></div></div><div
class="post-270 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-command-line-hacks category-howto category-networking category-security tag-apple tag-debian-linux tag-freebsd tag-linux tag-ubuntu tag-unix post_box" id="post-270"><div
class="headline_area"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/networking/nmap-command-examples-tutorials/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent link to Top 30 Nmap Command Examples For Sys/Network Admins">Top 30 Nmap Command Examples For Sys/Network Admins</a></h2><p
class="headline_meta">by <span
class="author vcard"><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/tips/about-us" rel="author" class="url fn">nixCraft</a></span> on <abbr
class="published" title="2012-11-26">November 26, 2012</abbr> &middot; <span><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/networking/nmap-command-examples-tutorials/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span
class="dsq-postid" rel="270 http://www.cyberciti.biz/?p=270">8 comments</span></a></span></p><p
class="headline_meta">in <span><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/open-source/command-line-hacks/" title="View all posts in Command Line Hacks" rel="category tag">Command Line Hacks</a>, <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/howto/" title="View all posts in Howto" rel="category tag">Howto</a>, <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/networking/" title="View all posts in Networking" rel="category tag">Networking</a>, <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/security/" title="View all posts in Security" rel="category tag">Security</a></span></p></div><div
class="format_text entry-content"><p><span
class="drop_cap">N</span>map is short for Network Mapper. It is an open source security tool for network exploration, security scanning and auditing. However, nmap command comes with lots of options that can make the utility more robust and difficult to follow for new users.<br/></p><p>The purpose of this post is to introduce a user to the nmap command line tool to scan a host and/or network, so to find out the possible vulnerable points in the hosts. You will also learn how to use Nmap for offensive and defensive purposes.</p><p
class="to_comments"><span
class="bracket">{</span> <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/networking/nmap-command-examples-tutorials/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span>8</span> comments</a> <span
class="bracket">}</span></p></div></div><div
class="post-243 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-hardware category-howto category-open-source category-security tag-debian-linux tag-linux tag-luks-disk-encryption post_box" id="post-243"><div
class="headline_area"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/hardware/howto-linux-hard-disk-encryption-with-luks-cryptsetup-command/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent link to HowTo: Linux Hard Disk Encryption With LUKS [ cryptsetup Command ]">HowTo: Linux Hard Disk Encryption With LUKS [ cryptsetup Command ]</a></h2><p
class="headline_meta">by <span
class="author vcard"><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/tips/about-us" rel="author" class="url fn">nixCraft</a></span> on <abbr
class="published" title="2012-10-19">October 19, 2012</abbr> &middot; <span><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/hardware/howto-linux-hard-disk-encryption-with-luks-cryptsetup-command/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span
class="dsq-postid" rel="243 http://www.cyberciti.biz/?p=243">11 comments</span></a></span></p><p
class="headline_meta">in <span><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/hardware/" title="View all posts in Hardware" rel="category tag">Hardware</a>, <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/howto/" title="View all posts in Howto" rel="category tag">Howto</a>, <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/open-source/" title="View all posts in Open Source" rel="category tag">Open Source</a>, <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/security/" title="View all posts in Security" rel="category tag">Security</a></span></p></div><div
class="format_text entry-content"><p>Dear nixCraft,<br/></p><p>I carry my Linux powered laptop just about everywhere. How do I protect my private data stored on partition or removable storage media against bare-metal attacks where anyone can get their hands on my laptop or usb pen drive while traveling?<br/></p><p>Sincerely,<br/><br
/> Worried about my data.</p><p
