class="bracket">{</span> <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/hardware/howto-linux-hard-disk-encryption-with-luks-cryptsetup-command/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span>11</span> comments</a> <span
class="bracket">}</span></p></div></div><div
class="post-149 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-command-line-hacks category-security tag-cracklib-check-command tag-linux tag-passwords post_box" id="post-149"><div
class="headline_area"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/security/linux-password-strength-checker/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent link to HowTo: Linux Check Password Strength With Cracklib-check Command">HowTo: Linux Check Password Strength With Cracklib-check Command</a></h2><p
class="headline_meta">by <span
class="author vcard"><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/tips/about-us" rel="author" class="url fn">nixCraft</a></span> on <abbr
class="published" title="2012-07-22">July 22, 2012</abbr> &middot; <span><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/security/linux-password-strength-checker/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span
class="dsq-postid" rel="149 http://www.cyberciti.biz/?p=149">2 comments</span></a></span></p><p
class="headline_meta">in <span><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/open-source/command-line-hacks/" title="View all posts in Command Line Hacks" rel="category tag">Command Line Hacks</a>, <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/security/" title="View all posts in Security" rel="category tag">Security</a></span></p></div><div
class="format_text entry-content"><p><span
class="drop_cap">U</span>sing the same password on different servers allows attackers to access your accounts if cracker manage to steal your password from a less secure server. This is true for online website accounts too. So solution is to create unique passwords for server accounts like your email, sftp and ssh accounts. General guideline to create a strong and unique password is as follows:</p><p
